<!DOCTYPE html><html lang="en"><head><meta charset="utf-8" /><title>Loops and Arrays</title><style type="text/css">body {	font-family: courier, monospace;	color:#FF6633;	}	.instructions {	color: #666666;	font-family: georgia, serif;	}	code {	color: #444;	font-weight: bold;	font-size: 1.1em;}</style></head><body><header><h1 class="instructions">Loops and Arrays</h1></header><article><h2 class="instructions">Using loops to get elements from arrays</h2><p class="instructions">When you are outputting array information, you can only retrieve one array element at a time unless you return to the array to get everything. Loops allow you to keep going back to the array to get all the elements it holds.</p><h3 class="instructions">Build an array and use a loop to get its elements.</h3><p class="instructions">Write an indexed array called <code>$spectrum</code> that holds the following values: red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, violet</p><!-- create the array here and use print_r() to view it. --><?php$spectrum = array('red', 'orange', 'yellow', 'green', 'blue', 'indigo', 'violet');echo '<pre>';print_r($spectrum);echo '</pre>';?><p class="instructions">Now, use a <code>foreach</code> loop to output each of the values for the array. Obviously, since we wrote the array ourselves, we can easily just output them one at a time, but often you do NOT know how many elements are in an array, or what their keys might be. Remember to unset the value of the variable you use to retrieve each element from the array during the loop.</p><!-- write script here --><?php //can call $value whatever you want because it is just a temporary variableforeach ($spectrum as $value) {	echo $value.'<br />';}?><h3 class="instructions">Build another array and use a loop to get its elements.</h3><p class="instructions">Write an associative array called <code>$food_colors</code> with five keys: red, green, yellow, purple, orange and five elements: strawberry, lettuce, banana, grapes, tangerine. It should be pretty obvious which food goes with which key.</p><!-- create the array here and use print_r() to view it. --><?php $food_colors = array('red' => 'strawberry','green' => 'lettuce','yellow' => 'banana','purple' => 'grapes','orange' => 'tangerine'	);echo '<pre>';print_r($food_colors);echo '</pre>';?><p class="instructions">Now, use a <code>foreach</code> loop to output each of the values for the array. Remember to unset the value of the variable you use to retrieve each element from the array during the loop.</p><!-- write script here --><?php foreach ($food_colors as $key => $value) {	echo $value.'<br />';}?><h2 class="instructions">Using Multidimensional Arrays</h2><p class="instructions">Using the multidimensional arrays from the previous exercise, output each of the array items using a nested <code>foreach</code> loop. Each array element needs to display on its own line.</p><!-- write scripts here --><?php $random_image = array(	array('filename' => 'blue.gif', 'alt' => 'blue rectangle', 'caption' => 'Big Blue Rectangle!'),	array('filename' => 'green.gif', 'alt' => 'green rectangle', 'caption' => 'Big Green Rectangle!'),	array('filename' => 'orange.gif', 'alt' => 'orange rectangle', 'caption' => 'Big Orange Rectangle!'),	array('filename' => 'pink.gif', 'alt' => 'pink rectangle', 'caption' => 'Big Pink Rectangle!'),	array('filename' => 'red.gif', 'alt' => 'red rectangle', 'caption' => 'Big Red Rectangle!'),	array('filename' => 'yellow.gif', 'alt' => 'yellow rectangle', 'caption' => 'Big Yellow Rectangle!')	);foreach ($random_image as $value) {	foreach ($value as $key => $value2) {		echo $value2.'<br />';	}}//changing things hereecho '<br />'; $meals = array(	'breakfast' => array('oatmeal', 'poached egg', 'toast', 'waffles'),	'lunch' => array('ham sandwich', 'burrito', 'cheeseburger', 'spinach salad'),	'dinner' => array('spaghetti', 'roast beef', 'pizza', 'mac \'n\' cheese')	);foreach ($meals as $key => $value) {	echo $key.': ';	foreach ($value as $value2) {		echo $value2.' ';	}	echo '<br />';}?><p class="instructions">What if you want each of the meals to display on its own line, with the meal itself at the beginning? (ex: breakfast: oatmeal poached egge toast waffles)? Write a script that does it! Remember, in associative arrays, the key is meaningful language, so you can output the variable that retrieves it.</p><!-- write script here --></article></body></html>